Pneumonia.

\section*{Introduction.}
- Pneumonia is an infection in one or both lungs caused by bacteria, viruses or fungi.
- The infection leads to inflammation in the air sacs of the lungs, which are called alveoli. The alveoli filled with fluid or pus, making it difficult to breathe.
- Both viral or bacterial pneumonia are contagious; This means they can spread from person to person through inhalation of airborne or droplets from a sneeze or cough.
- Pneumonia can affect one or both lungs. Pneumonia in both of your lungs is called bilateral or double pneumonia
- While all pneumonia is inflammation caused by an infection in the lungs, one may have different symptoms depending on whether the root cause is a virus, bacteria or fungi.
- Bacterial pneumonia tends to be more common and more severe than viral pneumonia. It's more likely to require a hospital stay. Bacterial pneumonia is usually treated with antibiotics. Viral pneumonia causes flu-like symptoms and is more likely to resolve on its own. You usually don't need specific treatment for viral pneumonia.
